summary.heading: Balanced appetite
summary.body:
You are genetically likely to have a normal appetite.

This means that your body is good at regulating your calorie intake, and you are more likely to regularly consume the correct amount of calories per day.

You should keep in mind however that all calories are not created equally. It is important that you get not only the right amount of fuel for your body but also that it comes from appropriate sources (for example unsaturated fats are better for you than saturated). Regular exercise, plenty of sleep and a balanced diet will help curb any cravings.

If you are interested in decreasing your appetite, moderate intensity aerobic exercise (<75% intensity for 30-90 minutes) has demonstrated as much as a 60% reduction in appetite immediately after the workout. High intensity exercise (>75% intensity) such as high intensity interval training (HIIT), has been found to be even more effective. The effect is not long lasting and we therefore recommend that you do regular, high intensity training sessions to get a consistent effect.

A problem many people have when it comes to managing their appetite is picturing how many calories are actually in their meals, especially if they are not cooking at home. Although many people know that fast food is high in calories, it may come as a surprise that a regular burger combo often contains as many as 1,700 kcal, or more than half of the average adult's daily requirement. A good option, if you struggle with this issue, is to prepare all of your meals for the day ahead of time so that you know that you have your exact calorie intake for the day sorted. Thus, you can avoid ordering something from a menu or throwing together ingredients in a pan, and accidentally blowing your calorie budget. 
Including lots of low calorie ingredients such as vegetables (for example a cup of carrot sticks only contains 50 kcal) is another easy trick, as with these foods you can eat more, without actually consuming a lot of calories.

summary.heading: Low risk of gluten sensitivity
summary.body:
You are genetically at a low risk of gluten sensitivity.

This means that gluten-containing products should not create an adverse effect, and removing gluten from your diet is unlikely to have any positive health benefits for you.

If this result comes as a surprise to you then it is possible that you instead have a wheat allergy or non-celiac gluten sensitivity (NCGS), or even irritable bowel syndrome (IBS). The symptoms for all three are similar, and therefore it is best to consult your doctor to determine the underlying cause of any problems. Do also check out your gene results for IBS, as this may help you understand the source of your problems.

If you do decide to cut gluten from your diet, you should be sure to replace gluten-containing foods with healthy alternatives. Many people replace whole grains with foods much higher in fats, which can lead to an overall increased calorie intake, and eventually weight gain. Another thing to remember is that whole grains are an excellent source of fibre, iron, folate, vitamin B12 (because most non gluten-free breakfast cereals are fortified) and zinc. Corn, amaranth and buckwheat are all whole grains that do not contain gluten and should be considered as good options for replacements if you do decide to cut gluten from your diet.

result.result: High Proportion of Fast Twitch Muscle Fibres

summary.heading: High proportion of fast twitch muscle fibres
summary.body:
You are genetically likely to have a higher proportion of fast twitch muscle fibres.

Most people with a predominance of these muscles will have a bigger overall physique, with visibly larger skeletal muscles. This is because fast-twitch muscle fibres grow in both strength and size in response to physical exercise, whereas slow-twitch muscles do not.

This muscle profile suggests that you would be more suited for power than endurance based training.

Fast twitch muscle fibres contract with high force but they are only able to sustain this effect for a few seconds before the muscle begins to tire. Athletes with a predominance of these muscle fibres are therefore very well suited to exercises such as lifting weights in short, explosive bursts.

This does not mean that you cannot practice endurance training. Fast-twitch muscle fibres are more adaptable than their slow twitch counterparts in that they can convert between two subtypes in response to training. This means that when you practice aerobic, endurance exercises, some of your type 2b ‘classical power’ fibres can be converted to type 2a ‘intermediate’ muscle fibres. This conversion increases your capacity for endurance based exercise and gives you an advantage in sports like middle distance running, or rugby, where both explosive power and cardio fitness are important.

It is also important to note that there are other important genetic factors that influence how well suited you are to power based training - check out your VO2 max potential, muscle size and growth, and overall endurance vs power profile to find out more.

summary.heading: Efficient use of dietary fat
summary.body:
You are genetically more likely to use your fat as a fuel e.g. for exercise and less likely to store it.

This means that you are less susceptible to gaining weight and that your body is effective at burning fat after physical activities. Nevertheless, excessive calorie intake will eventually lead to weight gain through increased fat storage.

It is also important to watch out for the kinds of fats you are consuming. You should consider replacing most of your saturated fat intake with unsaturated fats derived from nuts, seeds, fish and plant oils. Unsaturated fats are not only found in more healthy foods, but they also help prevent/remove visceral fat storage, which can have long term health consequences.

A healthy diet and regular exercise is still important to help you maintain a healthy weight. A diet containing some fats is necessary for your body to function optimally, and sticking to the mid to upper-range (30-40%) of the daily requirement is recommended for you. It is often suggested that high intensity interval training, in combination with long-distance cardiovascular exercise (such as running for more than 20 minutes) is the best combination of exercise when it comes to burning calories and fat stores.

If gaining weight is your goal, then the type of fat you are eating becomes even more important. In order to gain weight you need to either build muscle, or force your body to store excess calories as fat. Favouring foods containing unsaturated fats will decrease the chance that your body will store calories as visceral fat. However, this is only true up to a point, and despite your low sensitivity the recommended intake of 40% of your calories from fat should still be followed.

summary.body:
You might need a bit more vitamin C than the recommended daily dose, so make sure you at least consume this amount every day.

Consider increasing your intake of fruit and vegetables, in particular citrus fruits, tomatoes, potatoes and dark green vegetables. Cooking fruit and vegetables reduces their vitamin C content by around 30-40 %, so it is important to ensure you incorporate raw foods as well. summary.heading: Good uptake of vitamin D
summary.body:
You genetically have a good uptake of vitamin D

This means that you are good at using vitamin D. Even though you are genetically less susceptible to becoming vitamin D deficient, it is still essential to ensure you give your body the chance to produce sufficient amounts of vitamin D, especially if you have darker skin or live in areas, like Denmark, with less sunshine in the winter period.

Try exercising outdoors rather than in the gym, or going for a short walk during your lunch break rather than sitting inside. You also have to take into account how much bare skin is exposed to sunlight. You don’t need to tan or burn to get a sufficient amount of sunlight exposure, but you do need bare skin that is not protected by clothes or sunscreen. Should you find yourself stuck indoors for the majority of your days, consider vitamin D rich foods or supplements.

summary.heading: High risk of lactose sensitivity
summary.body:
You are genetically at risk of being sensitive to lactose.

Not everyone with this genotype has lactose intolerance, however your chances of having or developing lactose intolerance are higher than average. If you have already developed intolerance, you might already be familiar with the side effects of consuming lactose from a young age. They can range from abdominal pain and bloating to nausea and diarrhea beginning anywhere between 30 minutes to 2 hours after consumption. 

Sometimes, lactose intolerant people can still consume cheese and butter, because the fermentation process breaks down most of the lactose present in the milk. As a general rule, foods with a lactose content of less than 2 % are considered safe, but figuring out how much your body can handle usually requires some trial and error. 

All dairy products are not created equally, and even within a food group the lactose content depends on the exact recipe followed.

summary.heading: Balanced uptake of vitamin A
summary.body:
Your test results indicate that you are not genetically at risk of having low vitamin A levels.

If you have a healthy diet rich in vegetables and regularly consume dairy, eggs, oily fish or liver, then your vitamin A levels should be fine. Vitamin content from vegetables can be lost readily through over cooking, air exposure and peeling. Try to only cut fruit and vegetables just before you are about to eat them and into large chunks, as this helps to reduce the air exposure. Storing them in an air-tight container will also help reduce vitamin loss.

It is always considered best to consume vitamin A through food as you get the added benefits of other nutrients. If you find it hard to get enough vitamin A, supplements could be considered as an alternative.

summary.heading: Low sensitivity to alcohol
summary.body:
You are genetically less sensitive to alcohol intake.

This means you have specific variations in your genes that enable you to convert alcohol to energy faster. You are less sensitive to alcohol and the effects of alcohol will hit you at a slower pace. It will take a larger amount of alcohol intake before you lose your inhibitions and senses, and you are therefore more likely to drink more than others. This does not necessarily have an impact on your degree of hangover.

You should take care of your alcohol intake though, as you are also more prone to long term negative effects such as alcohol dependence, increased blood pressure and high cholesterol numbers if you drink excessively.

If you want to lose weight it is probably a good idea to stay away from alcoholic drinks. Your body will burn the energy from alcohol before any other energy sources because of alcohol’s toxicity to your body, and because the body cannot store alcohol. Therefore you are more likely to store fats in your body while you have alcohol in your system. If you do not want to give up on alcohol completely the best drinks will be the ones based on sparkling water so the amount of calories consumed will be diminished.

Alcohol affects a number of hormones that can influence your workout ability. Your testosterone levels will fall and your stress hormone (cortisol) will increase. The combination of these can lead to breakdown of muscle mass in the longer term. In the short term, it will hinder the formation of new muscle. Therefore, if you are serious about training you should drink in moderation or avoid alcohol consumption completely. You should also keep an eye on your blood sugar and water intake if you workout during or after alcohol intake as alcohol changes the level of these due to its dehydrating effect.

summary.heading: Low uptake
summary.body:
You are genetically at risk of having low levels of vitamin B12. 

This means that you might need more vitamin B12 than others, so make sure you consume the recommended daily amount every day, maybe even aim for the highest of the two recommendations.

Vitamin B12 deficiency is most commonly found in the elderly, vegans (vitamin B12 is only found in foods from animal sources) and breastfed babies of vegan mothers. Good sources of B12 include liver, meat, milk, cheese and eggs - almost anything of animal origin. 

A high level of vitamin B9 can hide B12 deficiency. It is important to keep a balanced uptake of both of these vitamins. Even if you do not have any deficiency symptoms, you are at risk of developing these on a long term. Unlock your B9 category to learn about your uptake of this vitamin.
